{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893087/1945083001/0291.xml":{"full_text":"THURSDAY, AUG. 30, 1945\nBrief Review Os State, National And World News During The Past Week\nMORE CLOTHING WILL\nBE AVAILABLE SOON\nWashington\u2014Clothes for wom\nen and children will be piled high\nin stores by November. So will\nthings like sheets and towels.\nMen\u2019s clothes will be less plen\ntiful.\nThat was the forecast by indus\ntry leaders and Government of\nficials.\nIt was the brightest authorita\ntive picture yet on the clothing\noutlook.\nThe garment prospect has\nchanged radically since the Jap\nanese surrender.\nThe main factor in the change\nwas the unexpected speed with\nwhich the army wiped out most\nof its plans for buying clothing\nmaterials.\nOne official even said the na\ntion can look forward to a\n\u201cChristmas shopper\u2019s paradise\u201d in\nwomen\u2019s and children\u2019s clothing.\nMost items of men\u2019s clothing\nwill be produced in good quanti\nty.\nShirts and shorts will be pro\nduced at a rate 90 to 95 percent\nof their 1939 volume, manufac\nturers predict.\nARE TO CONTINUE TO\nDRAFT MEN FOR ARMY\nWashington\u2014The army wants\n50,000 new men each month for\nthe present, regardless of wheth\ner Japan is occupied peacefully,\nthe War Department said.\nAt the same time, Selective Di\nrector Lewis B. Hershey said\nSeptember draft calls would be\nf for 63,000 men\u2014so,ooo for the\narmy and 13,000 for the navy.\nThe navy calls, he told a reporter,\nwould represent a sharp reduction\nfrom the 25,000 to 30,000 men it\nhad been getting. Before Japan\nWANTED\nChestnut Wood Tan Bark\nO. P. A. CEILING PRICES PAID\nWilkes Extract Works\nNORTH WILKESBORO, NORTH CAROLINA\n-w\u2014.^BMSjir--\nS J\ns\nJM|F\u201c j\nf Jill\nNo discharge Button\nfor THIS Veteran- 7\nBut look at its service record! Thousands of Greyhound\nbuses serving in the battle of transportation have done a\ntremendous job since Pearl Harbor and they\u2019ve piled\nup a lot of points\nServing out-of-the-way military camps Taking part F\nin vital military movements Taking men directly\nto their homes on precious furloughs Serving many 5Ss/2?SP\u00a7\\\nmilitary hospitals where no other transportation is avail\nable Getting workers to and from war factories. \\ByISSSp\nThese Super-Coaches have earned their points... but there\u2019s WS/\nno discharge in sight\nSX7ta^ h V d Wi ma great de n ttn7 d min P r X:!\nsp ion. You can help us meet this crisis by planning men in its service who\nr your travel wisely. Arrange your trips in advance get are wcarin this World\nyour tickets early avoid week-end crowds. ar 11 Service Em-\nin the days to come we\u2019ll have finer coaches, better service to\ngive you more luxurious highway travel than ever before.\nUNION BUS TERMINAL\nPhone 90 West Jefferson, N. C.\n'began surrender negotiations the\narmy was inducting about 80,0U0\nI a month.\nThe War Department issued a\nstatement which termed \u201cerro\nnous\u201d published report that fur\nther reduction would be made in\nselective Service calls if General\ni MacArthur\u2019s occupation of Japan\nwas peaceful.\nAny cut in the 50,000-a-month\nI draft rate, the department assert\ned, will depend upon the rate at\nwhich men volunteer for duty in\noccupational forces.\ndr. McDonald heads\nPOLIO DRIVE AGAIN\nChapel Hill\u2014Basil O\u2019Connor,\nchairman of the __ational Infan\ntile Paralysis Foundation, has ap-\nI pointed Dr. Ralph McDonald of\nWinston-Salem, State chairman of\nthe annual polio campaign for the\nfourth successive year, it was an\ni nounced this week at State cam\npaign headquarters.\nIn accepting the appointment,\nDr. McDonald said plans for the\ncampaign already are being map\nped and that county quotas will\nbe announced during the Fall.\nHe pointed out that contribu\ntions from North Carolina citizens\nlast year set a new all-time high\nwith a total of $501,700 as com\npared to $178,000 the previous\nyear.\nThe people of North Carolina\n\u201cha ze always done their full part\nin the fight against infantile pa\nralysis, and the need at this time\nis greater than ever before,\u201d Dr.\nMcDonald said.\n\u201cWe in North Carolina have\nI benefited so much from the re\nsources of the National Founda\ntion for Infantile Paralysis that\nour 1946 drive will reflect our\ngratitude as well as our interest\nin helping others.\nWashington Is Rushing Plans\nTo Re-convert Private Firms\nGEN. DE GAULLE VISITS\nGRAVE OF ROOSEVELT\nHyde Park\u2014Gen. Charles de\nGaulle, provisional President of\nFrance, paid a long delayed call\non Franklin D. Roosevelt this\nweek.\nHis face somber and evidently\nmasking strong emotion, he plac\ned a simple wreath of green lau\nrel on the grave of the 32nd Pres\nident of the United States in the\nRose Garden of the Roosevelt es\ntate.\nIt was the best substitute pos\nsible for the visit Mr. Roosevelt\nsought with de Gaulle last Janu\nary while he was en route home\nfrom the Yalta conference and\nwhich de Gaulle declined, and\nfor the visit de Gaulle was ar\nranging to pay Mr. Roosevelt in\nWashington at the time of his\ndeath.\nOCCUPATION OF JAPAN\nGOING TO BE SLOW\nOkinawa\u2014American reconnais\nsance units will enter Tokyo as\nsoon as practicable but observers\nbelieved this week that troops\nwill not occupy the capital of Ja\npanese proper for weeks or even\nmonths.\nThe city was ravaged by Ameri\ncan air raids. One of the Japan\nese envoys who went to Manila\nwas quoted here as saying it was\n\u201cblown to hell\u201d and that the U.\nS. Army will have to look else\nwhere for necessary headquar\nters and barracks facilities.\nIt also is believed here that it\nwill take as long as five months\nto complete the occupation of the\nJapanese mainland and that 500,-\n000 American troops will be land\ned by that time.\nOne of the chief present wor\nries of officers in charge of oc\ncupying forces is protecting Gen.\nDouglas MacArthur when he\nmakes his first appearance in Ja\npan. One source pointed out that\nit would take only one man to\ntake a shot at MacArthur and\nthen \u201cwe\u2019d all be in an awful\nway.\u201d\nA new modified cotton fabric\nthat will not mildew or rot has\nbeen developed by scientists of\nthe USDA.\nfHE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON. N. C.\nWashington\u2014The Government\nis going all out to get private\nplants back into peacetime pro\nduction \u2014giving second emphasis\nto the Government plants.\nOfficials believe many of the\nfederally owned factories will\nstand idle for years to come, and\nperhaps forever.\nThe aim now is to get the thou\nsands of privately owned plants\ncleared of the leftovers of muni\ntions production, paid off for\ntheir services, and refitted quick\nly for civilian goods manufactur\ning.\nTop officials now see the pri\nvate plants as the prime key to\nrapid reconversion and the prompt\nopening of job opportunities for\nveterans and laid-off war work\ners. They will get first attention.\nThis is the intent of Lieut. Gen.\nLevin H. Campbell, Jr., former\narmy chief of ordnance who was\nborrowed last week\u2014almost as\nsoon as hostilities stopped\u2014for a\npost in the Office of War Mobili\nzation and Reconversion.\nReconversion Director John W.\nSnyder shortly will name Camp\nbell his \u201cdeputy director for in\ndustrial reconversion,\u201d it was\nlearned.\nThe big \u201cwar baby\u201d plants and\nmany lesser Federal factories\nbuilt by the Government\u2014at a\ntotal cost approaching 15 billion\ndollars\u2014will be sold or leased as\nrapidy as takers can be found.\nBut officials know that many\nwon\u2019t find buyers, because a\npeacetime operator could not run\nthem at a profit. And they see no\nchance that the public could ab\nsorb their vast potential output\nfor many years ahead, if the\nplants were Government-run.\nThe Chrysler tank arsenal is an\nexample. It made transmissions\nvastly larger than any civilian\nvehicle could use. It could mass\nproduce steam shovels, but there\nis no mass market for steam shov\nels.\nSome 30 shell loading plants, all\nover the country, are of no known\nusefulness. They are not built or\nlocated to make anything that ci-\nHundreds of Odd Chairs\nPriced from \u20197.50 to \u201942.50\nMW*-' *W* H Hundreds of chairs, large and small. Our assortment includes\nrockers, pull-up chairs and many others that are wonderful val-\n'.-z- ues.\nBSgl BEDROOM SUITES\n~Period Suites, modernistic suites and others you will\nThese are suites of lasting beauty that will be a real\nadd\u2019.tion to your home. See ours before you make a selec\ntion.\nBeds anti New Heaters Mattresses\nCome in now and select your stove for frviivi $0.50\nwinter. Our selection includes heatrolas and riiceairomy Up\nothers. All sizes. All are at money saving\nWe have a big selection of P rices Big selection of mattresses,\nodd beds and springs. You Cook StOVCS All are real values. Invest ih\noften need an extra bed. See C k rHngeS j St Came rest in one or more o\u00a3 our\nus for real values. $37.50 tO $89.50 mattresses.\nLiving Room Suites PIANOS\nWell-made new living room suites with steel\nspring construction. An assortment of covers m-\neluding tapestry, velour and damask. OO tO X 4 O\nSee Us For Bargains In All New And Used Furniture.\nWe Sell On Easy Terms See Us For Your Furniture\nBurgess Furniture Company\nWest Jefferson, N. C. NEW AND USED FURNITURE Boone, N. C.\nGalax, Va. \u201cANTIQUES A SPECIALTY\u201d Marion, Va.\nOLD PEACETIME ISSUES\nTO CONFRONT CONGRESS\nWashington Reminiscent of\nthe early days of the New Deal,\nthe old peacetime issues\u2014jobs and\njobless\u2014bounded about Capitol\nHill again this week in advance\nof the reconvening of Congress.\nBroad areas of conflict already\nare visible as important commit\ntees return to Washington to draw\nthe patterns of back-to-normal\nlegislation.\nOther old timers coming back\ninto prominence include the ques\ntion of peacetime deficit financ\ning, raised Friday night by Her\nbert Brownell Jr., Republican na\ntional chairman, in a nation-wide\nbroadcast, and a suggestion by\nRep. Sabath (D-Ill.), rules com\nmittee chairman to renew last\nyear\u2019s controversial move for a\nFederal ballot for servicemen.\nCalled from its vacation by the\nurgency of redeploying the home\nfront from a war to peace foot\ning, Congress meets September\n5. This will be its first session\nsince the war ended. It also will\nbe the first since President Tru\nman officially kicked the lid off\npositions by telling reporters at a\nnews conference that the field is\nwide open.\nBig Helton News\nGuests of Mr. and Mrs. Guy\nWest, Sunday, were: Mrs. Lois\nMarsh and Brice Marsh, Aber\ndeen, Md., Mrs., Roise Johnson,\nMr. and Mrs. Marion Johnson,\nMr. Robert Johnson, Miss Nannie\nJohnson, Tuckerdale, Miss Paul\nine Blevins, Miss Ellen Tester\nman and Miss Ada West.\nMr. and Mrs. Louis Blevins are\nvisiting Mr. and Mrs. Edd Blevins\nthis week.\nMiss Ilene West was honored\nat a birthday party Saturday\nnight. Those present were Miss\nRuth Testerman, Miss Ellen Tes\nvilians use.\nIn any case, red tape, legal ob\nstacles, and the mere time of bar\ngaining will delay sales and leas\nes for months in many cases.\nMeanwhile an estimated 5,000,-\n000 persons will be unemployed\n\u2014looking for jobs\u2014within three\nmonths.\nBRONZE ARROWHEAD\nAWARDED PFC. OWEN\nPfc. Raymond L. Owen, son of\nMrs. Nart D. Owen, Rugby, Va.,\nmember of the Co. \u201cD\u201d, 141st In\nfantry of the veteran 36th \u201cTexas\u201d\nDivision, in Germany, has been\nawarded the Bronze Arrowhead\nto wear on his European Theater\nof Operations ribbon, according\nto information received here.\nThe Arrowhead has been award\ned for participation in the (Sal\nerno) (Riviera) invasion when\nhe made the D-Day amphibious\nassault.\nThe 36th Infantry Division has\nseen action on two D-Days: Italy\nand Southern France. To its\nterman, Walter Testerman, Cecil\nHash, Baltimore, Md.; Jimmy\nValton, Baltimore, Md.; L. Wood\nDeboard, Mrs. Lesie Hash and\nchildren. Refreshments were\nserved by Mrs. West.\nPROUD of\nyour BISCUITS!\nGood cooks deserve good flour SNOW\nGOOSE, the smooth, white flour that always\ndoes its part in turning out grand biscuits and.\npastries You\u2019ll be proud of the things you.\nbake with SNOW GOOSE FLOUR. Try a sack\nnext time you need flour.\nJSb k B B i i I/. 4?\nPAGE THREE\nPFC. HODGES AWARDED\nBRONZE STAR MEDAL\nWith The Finn Army, Italy\u2014\nPrivate First Class Dean B. Hodg\nes, of West Jefferson, recently?\nwas awarded the Bronze Star\nMedal for heroic achievement in\naction in Italy.\nHe served on the First Army\nfront in the 351st \u201cSpearhead\u2019*\nRegiment of the 88th \u201cBlue Devil\u2019*\"\nDivision.\nHis mother, Mrs. Texie Mae\nHodges, lives in West Jefferson.\ncredit are such battles as San>\nPietro and Cassino, the Rapido\nRiver and Anzio. It fought at\nMontelimar, where the Germant\nNineteenth Army was annihilated\nand drove across the Sainte Mar\nie Pass of the Vosges Mountains;.\nIt breached the powerful Sieg\nfried Line defenses at Wissem\nbourg and completed four hun\ndred days of actual combat plung\ning through Germany and deep in\nto Austria.","height":"27240","width":"19917"}}
